        p A proposition is a declarative sentence that have a value of True and False, but not both.
        br

        h3 Example
        p Letâ€™s have a couple of propositions.
        br
        blockquote
          p 1. Washington, D.C., is the capital of the United States of America.
          p 2. Toronto is the capital of Canada.
          p 3. 1+1=2.
          p 4. 2+2=3.
        br
        p Propositions 1 and 3 are true, whereas 2 and 4 are false.
        br
        p Consider the following sentences.
        br
        blockquote
          p 1. What time is it?
          p 2. Read this carefully.
          p 3. x+1=2.
          p 4. x + y = z.
        br
        p Sentences 1 and 2 are not propositions because they are not declarative sentences. Sentences 3 and 4 are not propositions because they are neither true nor false. Note that each of sentences 3 and 4 can be turned into a proposition if we assign values to the variables.
        p For example, if we look at sentence 3. If we assign values x to 1, then the statement will become true. If we assign values x to 2, then it will become false. And so on.
